# Countries that generated the highest revenue

location = ['top', 'bottom', 'right', 'left']

x = top_nations.values
ytick_labels = top_nations.index

# Setting the locale to format numbers with comma separators
locale.setlocale(locale.LC_NUMERIC, 'en_US.UTF-8')

# Creating a dictionary to map country codes to country names
label_mapping = {'AU': 'Australia', 'US': 'United States', 'JP': 'Japan', 'KR': 'Korea', 'FR': 'France'}

# Replacing the ytick labels using the mapping dictionary
ytick_labels_new = [label_mapping[label] for label in ytick_labels]

bar_c = plt.barh(ytick_labels_new, x, height = 0.5, color = 'lightgrey')

# Formatting labels with commas after every thousand from the second decimal place
formatted_labels = [locale.format_string('%.2f', value, grouping=True) for value in x]
plt.bar_label(bar_c, labels=formatted_labels, padding=10)

for l in location:
    plt.gca().spines[l].set_visible(False)

plt.title('Countries with the Highest Movie Revenue', pad = 20)
plt.ylabel('Countries')
plt.xlabel('Revenue')
plt.gca().patches[4].set_facecolor('#002147')
plt.xticks([])
plt.show()

# Possible Reason for the Revenue Drop between 2022 and 2023
# Count of Movies (by Genre) Produced in 2022

m_2022 = movie_clean[movie_clean['year'] == 2022]

# Grouping the filtered DataFrame by 'genre' and calculating the count and sum of 'revenue' for each group
genre_cnts_and_rev = m_2022.groupby('main_genre')['revenue ($)'].agg(['count', 'sum'])

# Resetting the index to make 'genre' a regular column instead of an index, and sorting by count.
genre_cnts_and_rev = genre_cnts_and_rev.reset_index().sort_values(by = 'count', ascending = False)

# Print the result
print(genre_cnts_and_rev)

# Count of Movies (by Genre) Produced in 2023

m_2023 = movie_clean[movie_clean['year'] == 2023]

# Grouping the filtered DataFrame by 'genre' and calculating the count and sum of 'revenue' for each group
genre_cnts_and_revss = m_2023.groupby('main_genre')['revenue ($)'].agg(['count', 'sum'])

# Resetting the index to make 'genre' a regular column instead of an index, and sorting by count
genre_cnts_and_revss = genre_cnts_and_revss.reset_index().sort_values(by = 'count', ascending = False)

# Print the result
print(genre_cnts_and_revss)
